Raw dev notes -- The Never-Ending Battle Against Information Overload (and Docker)

Okay, so this past couple of weeks has been a whirlwind on the personal info hub project. For anyone new, this whole thing is my attempt to wrangle the firehose of information I get daily – WhatsApp messages, newsletters, articles – and distill it into something digestible, usually a daily summary or "digest" generated by an LLM. It's my personal assistant, basically, trying to keep me sane and informed without drowning in noise.

This period was a mix of shoring up existing systems and pushing forward with new ingestion pipelines. A big win was finally tackling the massive message duplication issue; I found the root cause and purged over 2200 duplicate messages. That felt *good*. I also spent a ton of time on system robustness. The watchdog got a huge upgrade, now checking everything from disk usage and WAL files to memory and even doing weekly restarts. I added crash forensics and bumped log retention, which is going to be a lifesaver. The `keep_awake` logic for the display was refined, especially around Shabbat, moving from a problematic `asyncio.sleep` to a more robust skip-and-retry mechanism.

New features included getting email newsletter ingest working via Gmail IMAP polling, which is huge. I also started laying the groundwork for a Medium article pipeline, involving Gemini for filtering, Freedium for fetching, and some custom TOON-lite compression to make them digestible. The digest itself got smarter, ensuring all groups are represented and allowing for longer, more comprehensive summaries, plus separating out newsletter highlights. I also added some handy utility scripts for fetching/embedding and resending digests, which will be super useful for debugging and testing.

Man, there were some real head-scratchers though. The `keep_awake` stuff was a nightmare – turns out broadcasting `SC_MONITORPOWER` on Windows triggers "Modern Standby" which is the *opposite* of what I wanted. Had to revert that and find another way. The watchdog, while much improved, was a constant battle. Docker Desktop crashing, WSL issues, PowerShell variable syntax errors – it felt like I was fighting the OS as much as my own code. I even had to implement escalating Docker recovery scripts, from a simple restart to unregistering WSL. That's how deep the rabbit hole went.

The WhatsApp integration continues to be a source of frustration. Discovering that 6 groups are *permanently* failing to fetch messages with no upstream fix is a real bummer. It means I'm missing chunks of my personal data, and there's nothing I can do about it right now. Also, getting the RTL rendering right for WhatsApp digests was surprisingly fiddly, needing a regex fix to check the *first meaningful character* rather than just the first character. And of course, an LLM SDK upgrade (`google-genai`) threw an `AttributeError` until I figured out the new `ThinkingConfig` syntax. It's always something.

Honestly, this period felt like a grind, but a productive one. It's a constant reminder that building robust systems isn't just about writing features; it's about anticipating failure, building layers of resilience, and debugging obscure interactions between your code, the OS, and external APIs. The satisfaction of squashing those 2200 duplicates or getting the watchdog to reliably restart Docker is immense, even if it feels like I'm just patching holes in a leaky boat sometimes. It's a testament to the value of persistence and detailed logging. Every time I fix one of these deep-seated issues, I feel a little more confident in my ability to build something truly reliable.

Next up: Implement those admin API endpoints and get the full Medium pipeline running.
